1
00:00:00,400 --> 00:00:04,160
<i>In 2166, an immortal tyrant
named Vandal Savage</i>

2
00:00:04,240 --> 00:00:06,800
<i>conquered the world
and murdered my wife and child.</i>

3
00:00:06,880 --> 00:00:09,560
<i>I have assembled an elite team
to hunt him throughout time</i>

4
00:00:09,640 --> 00:00:11,240
<i>and stop his rise to power.</i>

5
00:00:11,320 --> 00:00:13,640
<i>Unfortunately,
my plan is opposed by the body.</i>

6
00:00:13,720 --> 00:00:16,840
<i>I'd sworn my allegiance
to the Time Masters.</i>

7
00:00:16,920 --> 00:00:21,040
<i>In the future, my friends may not be
heroes but if we succeed,</i>

8
00:00:21,120 --> 00:00:24,200
<i>they will be remembered as legends.</i>

9
00:00:26,160 --> 00:00:28,040
<i>Previously,
on</i>Legends Of Tomorrow...

10
00:00:28,120 --> 00:00:31,800
Ray! Ray, I need you! Please!
I thought you were dead.

11
00:00:31,880 --> 00:00:33,600
Well, not only did you fail
to capture Savage.

12
00:00:33,680 --> 00:00:36,120
You also exposed yourselves
and your powers to him,

13
00:00:36,200 --> 00:00:38,640
giving away the element of surprise
for now and all time.

14
00:00:38,720 --> 00:00:40,720
I let you go,
you'll deliver the Waverider.

15
00:00:40,800 --> 00:00:42,440
Boys, ship's all yours.

16
00:00:42,520 --> 00:00:44,320
You're a liability to the team.

17
00:00:44,400 --> 00:00:47,400
Only one of us is walking
out of here alive.

18
00:00:49,720 --> 00:00:52,360
{\an5}<i>One, two, 3.00, 4.00 rock</i>

19
00:00:52,440 --> 00:00:55,040
<i>Five, six, 7.00, 8.00 rock</i>

20
00:00:55,120 --> 00:00:56,120
<i>Nine, ten, 11.00</i>

21
00:00:56,200 --> 00:00:57,960
Tommy, promise me
you won't go too fast.

22
00:00:58,040 --> 00:01:00,000
You got to hold on
to something, honey.

23
00:01:00,080 --> 00:01:01,840
- Preferably me.
- Remember.

24
00:01:01,920 --> 00:01:03,320
Just because you stole
your grandma's wheels

25
00:01:03,400 --> 00:01:04,640
don't mean you got to drive like her.

26
00:01:04,720 --> 00:01:07,640
You run your mouth pretty fast.
Let's see if your car can keep up.

27
00:01:12,240 --> 00:01:13,360
Let's go!

28
00:01:33,120 --> 00:01:34,520
Tommy, watch it!

29
00:01:38,880 --> 00:01:40,600
<i>When it's eight, nine, ten, 11 too</i>

30
00:01:40,680 --> 00:01:43,240
<i>I'll be going strong
And so will you</i>

31
00:01:43,320 --> 00:01:45,880
<i>We're gonna rock
Around the clock tonight</i>

32
00:01:45,960 --> 00:01:48,440
<i>We're gonna rock, rock,
Rock till broad daylight</i>

33
00:01:48,520 --> 00:01:49,680
<i>We're gonna rock, gonna rock</i>

34
00:01:49,760 --> 00:01:52,080
<i>Around the clock tonight</i>

35
00:01:53,800 --> 00:01:56,200
Yo, James Dean! Are you...

36
00:01:59,680 --> 00:02:00,680
What's that?

37
00:02:03,880 --> 00:02:05,720
I think that's a comet or something.

38
00:02:06,760 --> 00:02:08,280
It's a meteorite...

39
00:02:09,200 --> 00:02:10,560
in point of fact.

40
00:02:11,360 --> 00:02:13,520
I was drawn to it as well.

41
00:02:15,120 --> 00:02:17,920
Your presence out here
was unexpected.

42
00:02:19,200 --> 00:02:21,600
Or perhaps that's just
another word for

43
00:02:22,800 --> 00:02:24,240
destiny.

44
00:02:37,360 --> 00:02:40,880
I'm not the only one whose vision
is blurry in their left eye, am I?

45
00:02:40,960 --> 00:02:42,680
- Oh.
- Seeing three of everything?

46
00:02:42,760 --> 00:02:43,760
That's normal, right?

47
00:02:43,840 --> 00:02:44,960
Yes, as I mentioned before,

48
00:02:45,040 --> 00:02:46,640
the effect of time travel
on the human body

49
00:02:46,720 --> 00:02:49,040
increases with the length
of each jaunt.

50
00:02:49,120 --> 00:02:51,720
- So, where are we?
- Harmony Falls, Oregon.

51
00:02:51,800 --> 00:02:53,560
According to Captain Baxter's intel,

52
00:02:53,640 --> 00:02:56,880
Savage makes an appearance
in this quaint little hamlet.

53
00:02:56,960 --> 00:02:59,160
What the hell is Savage
doing in Pleasantville?

54
00:03:01,040 --> 00:03:03,240
Murder, apparently.

55
00:03:03,320 --> 00:03:06,160
Several denizens of Harmony Falls
have been brutally slain

56
00:03:06,240 --> 00:03:07,320
and others have gone missing.

57
00:03:08,520 --> 00:03:09,720
Kind of like Rory.

58
00:03:09,800 --> 00:03:13,440
{\an5}Reports are vague but it seems like
the killer is an expert with knives.

59
00:03:13,520 --> 00:03:17,000
- That sounds like Savage's MO.
- Yeah, but serial killing isn't.

60
00:03:17,080 --> 00:03:19,520
Sounds pretty small-time for a guy
who's has coffee with Hitler.

61
00:03:19,600 --> 00:03:21,760
{\an5}Yeah, well, clearly we have to assume
that Savage has a larger

62
00:03:21,840 --> 00:03:23,080
more nefarious plan.

63
00:03:23,160 --> 00:03:26,680
{\an5}But since we've jumped back in time,
Savage isn't expecting us here.

64
00:03:26,760 --> 00:03:30,120
Savage is pretty good at hiding,
even in a small town

65
00:03:30,200 --> 00:03:31,960
so how do you plan to find him?

66
00:03:32,040 --> 00:03:33,920
By investigating these murders.

67
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:37,440
{\an5}Now, there has to be a common link
between the victims

68
00:03:37,520 --> 00:03:39,440
starting with the first.

69
00:03:39,520 --> 00:03:42,280
A piano teacher was found
slain in her home

70
00:03:42,360 --> 00:03:43,760
which is now on the market.

71
00:03:43,840 --> 00:03:45,880
There is, of course, crown molding.

72
00:03:45,960 --> 00:03:49,200
All original floors. Stucco ceiling.

73
00:03:49,680 --> 00:03:51,840
{\an5}There's a small room
above the garage

74
00:03:51,920 --> 00:03:53,960
suitable for live-in help.

75
00:03:54,040 --> 00:03:56,320
Oh, well, we don't need a maid.

76
00:03:56,400 --> 00:03:58,760
{\an5}My husband and I get along
just fine on our own.

77
00:04:00,200 --> 00:04:04,360
{\an5}You know, I have a lovely
Tudor style in another town.

78
00:04:04,440 --> 00:04:07,080
A more accepting one.

79
00:04:07,160 --> 00:04:08,760
Forward-thinking.

80
00:04:09,840 --> 00:04:11,640
No, that's... that's fine.

81
00:04:12,160 --> 00:04:13,800
I like my towns backward.

82
00:04:15,760 --> 00:04:17,680
Dr. Matt Miller was found murdered

83
00:04:17,760 --> 00:04:19,720
on the grounds of the asylum
where he worked.

84
00:04:19,800 --> 00:04:22,080
{\an5}The sanitarium is in need
of a replacement.

85
00:04:22,160 --> 00:04:24,520
It's a very impressive facility.

86
00:04:25,760 --> 00:04:29,160
{\an5}I did my doctoral thesis
on socio-pathology in relationship

87
00:04:29,240 --> 00:04:30,840
to serial murder, actually.

88
00:04:30,920 --> 00:04:32,400
{\an5}Well, that'll certainly come in
handy around here.

89
00:04:32,480 --> 00:04:37,040
{\an5}We've been short-staffed ever since
Dr. Miller's sudden demise.

90
00:04:37,120 --> 00:04:39,480
{\an5}Of course, I could never consider
accepting a position here

91
00:04:39,560 --> 00:04:43,080
without my faithful nurse/assistant.

92
00:04:43,160 --> 00:04:46,960
{\an5}Yes, well, she looks like
she'll fit right in.

93
00:04:50,040 --> 00:04:52,920
Meanwhile, Jefferson is the perfect
age to discern the facts

94
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:55,000
behind the disappearance
of three teenagers

95
00:04:55,080 --> 00:04:57,920
who went missing a week
before these murders began.

96
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,240
So, Raymond and Kendra
are shacking up

97
00:05:00,320 --> 00:05:04,080
{\an5}Sara's Nurse ratched
and Jax's the new kid in town.

98
00:05:04,160 --> 00:05:05,880
Where does that leave me?

99
00:05:16,200 --> 00:05:17,880
We're looking for the sheriff.

100
00:05:17,960 --> 00:05:20,200
Well, you found him. Bud Ellison.

101
00:05:20,960 --> 00:05:22,160
How can I help you, folks?

102
00:05:22,880 --> 00:05:24,520
Special Agent Rip Hunter.

103
00:05:24,600 --> 00:05:26,880
This is my partner, Leonard.

104
00:05:26,960 --> 00:05:29,760
{\an5}We are here to investigate
the serial murders

105
00:05:29,840 --> 00:05:33,280
{\an5}which have plagued this
sleepy old town of yours.

106
00:05:33,360 --> 00:05:34,800
Now, slow down there, buddy.

107
00:05:34,880 --> 00:05:37,400
{\an5}There ain't no serial killer
anywhere.

108
00:05:37,480 --> 00:05:39,640
{\an5}All we got is some
unexplained accidents is all.

109
00:05:39,720 --> 00:05:41,360
{\an5}How about you hand over
those case files

110
00:05:41,440 --> 00:05:43,160
so we can decide for ourselves?

111
00:05:44,120 --> 00:05:46,680
{\an5}Or we can come back
with a court order

112
00:05:46,760 --> 00:05:49,200
and a really nasty disposition.

113
00:05:51,440 --> 00:05:53,480
{\an5}Anything for our friends
at the bureau.

114
00:05:57,920 --> 00:05:59,520
Nice work, partner.

115
00:05:59,600 --> 00:06:01,280
You're not my partner.

116
00:06:01,360 --> 00:06:04,280
There's only one person
I ever trusted on this job,

117
00:06:05,320 --> 00:06:07,280
and we all know how that turned out.

118
00:06:10,400 --> 00:06:12,160
Schwinn Hornets.

119
00:06:12,240 --> 00:06:14,360
I had the very same one
when I was their age.

120
00:06:14,440 --> 00:06:18,640
Seeing white picket fences
and perfect family houses

121
00:06:18,720 --> 00:06:20,800
it's enough to make one nostalgic.

122
00:06:20,880 --> 00:06:23,880
- Or nauseated.
- Oh, come on, Ms. Lance.

123
00:06:23,960 --> 00:06:28,760
Even someone as jaded as yourself
can't deny how idyllic this time was.

124
00:06:28,840 --> 00:06:29,880
Yeah.

125
00:06:30,560 --> 00:06:32,880
- If you're white.
- And a man.

126
00:06:32,960 --> 00:06:36,360
- And straight. And...
- Okay, okay. I get the point.

127
00:06:36,440 --> 00:06:39,480
Dude, even if this town
wasn't full of small-minded idiots

128
00:06:39,560 --> 00:06:41,600
it'd still be creepy as hell.

129
00:06:41,680 --> 00:06:43,880
I used to watch all these old
horror movies with my mom,

130
00:06:43,960 --> 00:06:46,360
and they all started off
in places like this.

131
00:06:46,880 --> 00:06:49,480
See, first it's all perfect
and then, boom,

132
00:06:49,560 --> 00:06:51,040
some alien monster beast thing

133
00:06:51,120 --> 00:06:52,440
starts killing kids on Lovers Lane.

134
00:06:52,520 --> 00:06:54,000
- Oh.
- I'm telling you, man.

135
00:06:57,560 --> 00:06:58,560
What is it?

136
00:06:59,520 --> 00:07:01,320
An unhappy cheerleader.

137
00:07:01,400 --> 00:07:03,040
Now, that is scary.

138
00:07:03,120 --> 00:07:05,880
That girl was from the newspaper
articles Rip showed us.

139
00:07:05,960 --> 00:07:07,440
She knows the guys that went missing.

140
00:07:07,520 --> 00:07:09,920
Perhaps she can illuminate us
as to their whereabouts.

141
00:07:11,120 --> 00:07:12,840
Dude, can you not just say,

142
00:07:12,920 --> 00:07:14,760
"Hey, Jax, why don't you
go talk to her

143
00:07:14,840 --> 00:07:16,040
and find out what she knows?"

144
00:07:16,120 --> 00:07:17,440
Like a normal person.

145
00:07:17,520 --> 00:07:19,920
Hey, Jax,
why don't you just go do that?

146
00:07:20,680 --> 00:07:22,520
All right. We mustn't dawdle.

147
00:07:22,600 --> 00:07:24,440
I believe our lunch hour
is nearly at an end.

148
00:07:25,200 --> 00:07:27,560
Come along, Nurse.

149
00:07:27,640 --> 00:07:29,080
Just so you know

150
00:07:29,160 --> 00:07:32,280
Ra's al Ghul taught me
how to kill someone slowly,

151
00:07:32,360 --> 00:07:34,760
over the course of days.

152
00:07:41,400 --> 00:07:43,320
Hey, you mind if I sit?

153
00:07:44,800 --> 00:07:47,200
- You can't sit with him.
- What is up with them?

154
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:53,440
I... I don't think
they've seen anyone.

155
00:07:53,520 --> 00:07:55,440
Dip their fries in their milk
shake before?

156
00:07:57,200 --> 00:07:58,200
Oh.

157
00:07:58,880 --> 00:07:59,880
Don't knock it
till you tried it, girl.

158
00:07:59,960 --> 00:08:01,040
No.

159
00:08:02,480 --> 00:08:03,640
Okay.

160
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:11,240
- Okay, that's really good. Right?
- Yeah.

161
00:08:11,960 --> 00:08:13,040
I'm Jax.

162
00:08:13,560 --> 00:08:16,240
- Betty.
- Nice to meet you, Betty.

163
00:08:16,320 --> 00:08:17,400
Hey, Betty.

164
00:08:17,960 --> 00:08:20,280
Just because your boyfriend went AWOL

165
00:08:20,360 --> 00:08:22,640
doesn't mean you have to slum it
with this loser.

166
00:08:23,960 --> 00:08:25,800
Why don't you do yourself
a favor, Biff?

167
00:08:26,480 --> 00:08:30,320
Keep walking before you really,
really embarrass yourself.

168
00:08:36,400 --> 00:08:38,640
What? You want to take a swing at me?

169
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:43,720
Hey. Let's go.

170
00:08:45,120 --> 00:08:46,320
This isn't over.

171
00:08:49,120 --> 00:08:51,800
I am so sorry about that.

172
00:08:51,880 --> 00:08:53,520
- Where were we?
- No, that was amazing.

173
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:00,520
Do you want to hang out
tomorrow night?

174
00:09:01,320 --> 00:09:02,560
- Yeah.
- Yeah?

175
00:09:02,640 --> 00:09:04,200
- It's a date.
- Okay.

176
00:09:06,680 --> 00:09:10,120
<i>I was caught by your kisses</i>

177
00:09:10,200 --> 00:09:13,040
Well, now that we're done moving in,
care to dance?

178
00:09:14,600 --> 00:09:15,600
Sure.

179
00:09:15,680 --> 00:09:17,760
<i>Locked in your arms</i>

180
00:09:17,840 --> 00:09:19,560
<i>There's no mistake</i>

181
00:09:19,640 --> 00:09:24,560
So, yesterday, we kissed
and now, today, we're married.

182
00:09:24,640 --> 00:09:25,920
Okay, I know it seems like
we're moving fast

183
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:27,520
but this is all pretend.

184
00:09:27,600 --> 00:09:29,240
Soon as we get a divorce

185
00:09:30,040 --> 00:09:31,160
we'll figure us out.

186
00:09:31,680 --> 00:09:32,840
In the meantime

187
00:09:33,960 --> 00:09:35,240
doesn't mean
we can't have fun with it.

188
00:09:37,800 --> 00:09:39,080
This is a waste of time.

189
00:09:39,160 --> 00:09:42,440
We should be out there looking
for Savage, not playing doctor.

190
00:09:42,520 --> 00:09:43,520
You know what I mean.

191
00:09:43,600 --> 00:09:45,920
I'd like to think that in a town
with multiple murders

192
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:47,560
and missing teenagers,

193
00:09:47,640 --> 00:09:51,160
the local insane asylum would be
fertile ground for clues.

194
00:09:51,240 --> 00:09:53,520
Let's start by reviewing
the files of every inmate

195
00:09:53,600 --> 00:09:55,520
with a history of violence.

196
00:09:56,280 --> 00:09:59,880
If you wouldn't mind getting me
those files, Nurse?

197
00:10:01,280 --> 00:10:04,160
Literally for days.

198
00:10:17,520 --> 00:10:19,640
Is that a new perfume I smell?

199
00:10:19,720 --> 00:10:21,400
You know, if you're trying
to drive everyone crazy

200
00:10:21,480 --> 00:10:23,680
I have to tell you, it's working.

201
00:10:23,760 --> 00:10:25,040
I'm very busy right now.

202
00:10:25,120 --> 00:10:26,480
You know what your problem is?

203
00:10:26,560 --> 00:10:28,840
You don't know
how to have a good time.

204
00:10:28,920 --> 00:10:32,600
Now, what you need is a man
who can show you one.

205
00:10:40,920 --> 00:10:41,960
Thank you.

206
00:10:42,640 --> 00:10:44,120
That was incredible.

207
00:10:44,200 --> 00:10:46,920
Well, maybe next time,
he'll take no for an answer.

208
00:10:48,640 --> 00:10:51,040
It's not just him.

209
00:10:51,720 --> 00:10:53,880
Most of the doctors here
are looking for a good time

210
00:10:53,960 --> 00:10:55,960
and most of the nurses all say yes

211
00:10:56,040 --> 00:10:57,960
because they're looking
to get married.

212
00:10:58,040 --> 00:11:00,000
Oh. Not you, though.

213
00:11:00,800 --> 00:11:03,880
I'm not really looking for a husband.

214
00:11:05,520 --> 00:11:07,040
Today's my first day.

215
00:11:07,760 --> 00:11:09,400
Care to give the new girl a tour?

216
00:11:13,800 --> 00:11:16,360
The files you asked for, Doctor.

217
00:11:16,440 --> 00:11:18,280
Excellent, Nurse.

218
00:11:18,360 --> 00:11:20,600
I could also go for a cup of coffee.

219
00:11:20,680 --> 00:11:23,760
Me too. Black. Two sugars.

220
00:11:26,400 --> 00:11:27,760
And the cafeteria's over there.

221
00:11:27,840 --> 00:11:30,880
It's better than what we serve
the patients but not by much.

222
00:11:30,960 --> 00:11:32,080
Oh.

223
00:11:33,160 --> 00:11:34,440
What's down there?

224
00:11:35,040 --> 00:11:38,160
Oh, that's Hall H,
the restricted ward.

225
00:11:38,240 --> 00:11:40,240
It's for Dr. Knox's patients.

226
00:11:40,320 --> 00:11:41,880
Violent psychotics.

227
00:11:42,920 --> 00:11:45,680
That part of the tour
is worth skipping.

228
00:11:49,640 --> 00:11:50,680
Coming!

229
00:11:51,200 --> 00:11:52,240
I'm coming.

230
00:11:53,560 --> 00:11:56,360
- Welcome to the neighborhood.
- Thank you.

231
00:11:56,440 --> 00:12:00,960
- Thank you so much, Miss.
- Mrs. Knox.

232
00:12:01,040 --> 00:12:04,960
Gail Knox and this is my husband,
Curtis.

233
00:12:05,040 --> 00:12:06,360
Lovely to meet you.

234
00:12:46,320 --> 00:12:48,720
I'm sorry, have... have
we met before?

235
00:12:48,800 --> 00:12:50,280
I... I doubt it.

236
00:12:50,360 --> 00:12:55,000
I, we just moved in
from way out of town.

237
00:12:55,080 --> 00:12:56,800
I hope you like tuna surprise.

238
00:12:56,880 --> 00:12:59,000
Are you kidding?
I love tuna surprise.

239
00:12:59,080 --> 00:13:00,400
Oh, my God, Raymond!

240
00:13:00,480 --> 00:13:05,040
These are our new neighbors,
Curtis and Gail.

241
00:13:05,120 --> 00:13:08,120
- What a surprise.
- Tuna surprise.

242
00:13:08,680 --> 00:13:09,680
So many surprises.

243
00:13:09,760 --> 00:13:12,280
Well, another reason why we dropped
by was to let you know

244
00:13:12,360 --> 00:13:14,000
that we are having a soiree tonight.

245
00:13:14,080 --> 00:13:16,480
Stop by any time after 8.00.
We're just across the street.

246
00:13:16,560 --> 00:13:19,400
- Don't bother to ring the bell.
- No, you just walk right on in.

247
00:13:20,560 --> 00:13:22,040
It's that kind of neighborhood.

248
00:13:22,760 --> 00:13:26,960
Savage doesn't think I recognize him,
